1. Introduction

1.1 Discussion

This analysis is to determine how the popularity of the episodes of the Big Bang Theory relate to the content and production of the show as expressed in the available data. There are many variables available that describe each episode, such as the AirDate, Director, and the number of lines spoken by a range of characters.

1.2 Data Mutation

First, let us read in the data.

BigBangTheory = read_csv("BigBangTheory.csv", col_types = cols())

We want to mutate the data in order to perform effective analysis:

BigBangTheory %>% mutate(AirDate = as.Date(AirDate, format="%m/%d/%Y"),  Director = factor(Director),  
Season = as.numeric(sub("_.*", "", ID)),  Episode = as.numeric(sub(".*_", "", ID)),  
ChuckLorre = factor(ifelse(grepl("Chuck Lorre",Writer),"Yes","No")),  Day = weekdays(AirDate),  
TotalLines = Leonard+Sheldon+Penny+Howard+Raj+Leslie+Bernadette+Amy+Stuart+Emily+Mary+Zack+Bert+Janine+Wil) -> BigBangTheory
BigBangTheory$Director = relevel(BigBangTheory$Director, ref="Mark Cendrowski")

AirDate is now formatted as a date.
Director is now a factor.
Season and Episode have been added for convenience.
ChuckLorre is a Yes/No factor, determining whether Chuck Lorre was involved in that episode or not.
Day is the day of the week the episode was aired.
TotalLines is the total lines spoken during each episode by all the actors given combined.

From the numerical summary of the data, we can tell that there were a total of 231 episodes of The Big Bang Theory over Seasons 1-10, which ran from 2007 to 2017.
The main Director of the show was Mark Cendrowski.

Before looking into the ratings, it is useful to know how involved each character was in the show, as from the summary we can see some characters barely spoke at all:

The Characters Emily, Wil, Zack, Leslie, Bert, Mary and Janine did not appear in many episodes. Due to this it is important to note they will not be ideal predictors for a linear model, as there is hardly any evidence supporting that they had any effect.

2 The Effect of Air Date on the Ratings

Now we want to analyse whether the Air Date had an effect on the ratings.

ggplot(BigBangTheory, aes(x=AirDate, y=Rating)) + geom_point(aes(colour=factor(Season))) + labs(colour="Season") + ggtitle("Ratings of BBT Over Time") + geom_smooth(method="lm")
`geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

We see immediately that the later the AirDate, the lower the rating. But did the rating of episodes change within each Season?

2.1 The Rating of Episodes Within Each Season

Here are some graphical representations of how the rating of episodes changes throughout each season.

ggplot(BigBangTheory, aes(x=Episode, y=Rating, colour=factor(Season))) + geom_line() + scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1,24)) + scale_y_continuous(limits = c(6.5,9.5), breaks = seq(6.5,10.0,0.5)) + ggtitle("Episode ratings throughout each season") + labs(colour="Season")

ggplot(BigBangTheory,aes(Episode, Rating)) + geom_line() + facet_grid(rows = vars(Season)) + ggtitle("Episode ratings throughout each season")

To determine whether rating of episodes varied throughout the season, we can consider a linear model with Rating as the response and Episode as the predictor. As not all seasons have the same number of episodes, we instead consider ‘percentage of the way through the current season’ as our predictor. We add ‘Percentage’ as a variable in our data:

  BigBangTheory =  BigBangTheory %>% mutate(Percentage = 
      ifelse(Season == 1, 100 * Episode/ nrow(BigBangTheory %>% filter(Season==1)), 
      ifelse(Season == 2, 100 * Episode/ nrow(BigBangTheory %>% filter(Season==2)), 
      ifelse(Season == 3, 100 * Episode/ nrow(BigBangTheory %>% filter(Season==3)), 
      ifelse(Season == 4, 100 * Episode/ nrow(BigBangTheory %>% filter(Season==4)), 
      ifelse(Season == 5, 100 * Episode/ nrow(BigBangTheory %>% filter(Season==5)), 
      ifelse(Season == 6, 100 * Episode/ nrow(BigBangTheory %>% filter(Season==6)), 
      ifelse(Season == 7, 100 * Episode/ nrow(BigBangTheory %>% filter(Season==7)), 
      ifelse(Season == 8, 100 * Episode/ nrow(BigBangTheory %>% filter(Season==8)), 
      ifelse(Season == 9, 100 * Episode/ nrow(BigBangTheory %>% filter(Season==9)), 
                          100 * Episode/ nrow(BigBangTheory %>% filter(Season==10))))))))))))

We fit a model using Percentage as the predictor and Rating as the response.

pmod = lm(Rating ~ Percentage, BigBangTheory)

To see if Percentage is a significant predictor, we test the null hypothesis \(H_0: \beta = 0\) vs. the alternative hypothesis \(H_1: \beta \neq 0\).

library(broom)
tidy(pmod)
# A tibble: 2 x 5
  term        estimate std.error statistic   p.value
  <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>
1 (Intercept) 8.03       0.0622    129.    6.69e-216
2 Percentage  0.000199   0.00104     0.191 8.49e-  1

We see that the p-value of the t-statistic is 0.8491. This is a very high p-value so we do not reject the null hypothesis and Percentage is not a significant predictor. Hence we conclude that rating did not change within each season; ratings did not generally increase or decrease throughout.

This is very useful for us to know - since the ratings within each season generally remained stable, the AirDate and Season can be used interchangably in our models depending on what is required.

3.1 A Model to Determine Significance of the Predictors

Our initial model will include all the predictors we have available:

lmod = lm(Rating~Season+Director+ChuckLorre+Leonard+Sheldon+Penny+Howard+Raj+Leslie+Bernadette+Amy+Stuart+Emily+Mary+Zack+Bert+Janine+Wil+Day, BigBangTheory)

This clearly has too many predictors. It is best for us to immediately simplify this model:

lmodr = step(lmod, trace=FALSE)

We need to check the diagnostics of this model.

dmodr = augment(lmodr)

No particular residual has a high leverage, so no need for outliers to be removed if there are any.

dmodr = augment(lmodr)
ggplot(dmodr,aes(.fitted,.resid)) + geom_point() + geom_hline(yintercept = 0) + xlab("Fitted") + ylab("Residuals")

There is no non-constant variance, no non-linearity and no excessive outliers, so this is fine.

ggplot(dmodr,aes(sample=.std.resid)) + stat_qq() + stat_qq_line()

A little divergence on the upper tail but overall safe to assume errors are normally distributed.

Can safely assume this model is appropriate to use in determining significance of the variables.

3.2 Searching for Outliers in our Model

The largest studentized residuals for the BigBangTheory Rating model sorted by absolute value are:

BigBangTheory = column_to_rownames(BigBangTheory,"ID") #Changing ID to rownames for better idenification of each episode in the dataset
tail(sort(abs(rstudent(lmodr))))
     169      138      144      231       62      194 
2.462661 2.646711 2.853903 3.103582 3.134113 4.403043

We compute the critical value for declaring an outlier using the Bonferroni correction as:

qt(.05/(231*2),231-2-1)
[1] -3.75942

The episode 9_11 meets the outlier criterion by exceeding 3.75942 in absolute value.

This suggests that the Season is a very significant variable, and adds a lot of explanatory power even when we know the other predictors. The Day of the week and how many lines Leonard has are also significant predictors in the model determining the Rating. Penny is not a significant predictor in the model yet she was included - this suggests she has little to no overall effect on the rating, but can be somewhat useful alongside other predictors in determining the Rating.

p1 = plot(effect("Season",lmodr))
p2 = plot(effect("Leonard",lmodr))
p3 = plot(effect("Penny",lmodr))
p4 = plot(effect("Day",lmodr))
grid.arrange(p1,p2,p3,p4)

As can be seen with the effects plots, later seasons generally had more poorly rated episodes in them. The more Leonard spoke, the less popular the episode was in general, and episodes aired on a Thursday were generally more highly rated. Penny appears to have a somewhat positive but not conclusive effect on the Rating.

Something to note is the fact that in our initial graphs Leonard appeared to have a somewhat positive effect on the Rating. Let us explore this:

lm(Rating ~ Leonard, BigBangTheory) %>% tidy()
# A tibble: 2 x 5
  term        estimate std.error statistic   p.value
  <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>
1 (Intercept)  7.80      0.0753     104.   2.67e-194
2 Leonard      0.00546   0.00160      3.41 7.59e-  4

When used as a singular predictor, Leonard does indeed have a significant positive effect on the Rating. This is due to the correlation between AirDate and Leonard, as shown below:

BigBangTheory2 %>% select(AirDate,Leonard) %>% cor()
           AirDate    Leonard
AirDate  1.0000000 -0.4937715
Leonard -0.4937715  1.0000000

Leonard is heavily negatively correlated to the AirDate. Since the AirDate is a much more significant predictor in determining the Rating, when it is not involved in the linear model the relationship between it and the predictors actually become much more relevant than the direct relationship between the predictors and the Rating. So this explains why Leonard appears to have a positive effect in our graphs, when in actuality it is negative.

4 Further Exploration of the Model

4.1 Why is the Day relevant?

We should also explore why the Day may have had an effect on the rating.

This is a plot to visualise which episode aired on either day:

ggplot(BigBangTheory, aes(Season, Rating, colour = (Day))) + geom_point() + labs(colour = 'Day')

Interestingly, for the first three seasons episodes were aired on a Monday, while the other seasons aired on a Thursday, bar a handful of episodes. The fact the Day is significant suggests that the first three seasons did not rate as highly as expected, when taking the assumption that there is a linear relationship between the Rating and the AirDate.

The graph does appear to be not quite linear. However, our model assumptions held - it was acceptable to assume linearity between the Rating and the AirDate. The Day the episode aired may have had a genuine impact, for example Monday is a less favoured day, therefore people watching on that day could have had their opinions of the episode influenced by this. It is hard to be certain of the effect.

4.2 Why is Chuck Lorre not relevant?

Chuck Lorre is known as the King of Sitcoms, yet he was removed when simplifying our model. Let us see why:

ggplot(BigBangTheory,aes(AirDate,Rating,color=ChuckLorre)) + geom_point()

This plot graphically describes the difference between the episodes where Chuck Lorre was involved and where he was not involved. The coloured dots are very mixed suggesting there is very little if any correlation between Chuck Lorre’s writing and the Rating.

BigBangTheory %>% t.test(Rating ~ ChuckLorre, data=.)

 mean in group No mean in group Yes 
         8.001681          8.073214

The p-value is high when evaluating Chuck Lorre as a singular predictor. It is safe to say that he did not have an effect on the popularity of the episodes.

5. Other Comments

5.1 Raj

Viewers of the Big Bang Theory will know that Raj is known for his quietness, but are there particular characters who encourage or discourage him from speaking?

To test this, let us form a model with ‘Raj’ as the response and the other characters as the predictors.

rmod = lm(Raj ~ Leonard + Sheldon + Penny + Howard + Leslie + Bernadette + Amy + Stuart + Emily + Mary + Zack + Bert + Janine + Wil, BigBangTheory)
rmodr = step(rmod, trace=FALSE)
summary(rmodr)

From this we see that the significant predictors are Leonard, Sheldon, Penny, Howard, Bernadette, and Emily. The characters who discourage Raj from speaking are Leonard, Sheldon, Penny, and Bernadette. Howard and Emily instead appear to encourage Raj to speak.

As we know from the introduction to this report the number of lines of characters are correlated. This could be because there are characters who live or work together for example.
We revisit the correlation table:

In the introduction it was discussed that Leonard, Penny and Sheldon are all positively correlated to each other, but negatively correlated against Howard and Raj, who have a positive correlation with each other. This means that it is hard to determine which of Leonard, Penny and Sheldon drove the negative relationship with Raj - from the linear model it is implied they are all significant but since they heavily influence each other it is hard to give a definitive statement as to what specifically caused the negative relationship.

From our general knowledge of the show, this makes sense. Howard is Raj’s best friend, and Emily is a girl he briefly dates, therefore you would expect them to encourage him to talk more. Bernadette is Howard’s wife, so when Howard is spending time with her he is not spending time with Raj - meaning Raj speaks less. The discouragement from Leonard, Sheldon and Penny may be due to the fact that the plot generally does not have them interact with eachother often, so episodes that are more centric towards them are less likely to have Raj included. So the ‘discouragement’ and ‘encouragement’ from other characters to make Raj speak more could just be a consequence of the plot, as the only information we have is the lines spoken by each character in each episode, with no knowledge as to what these lines actually are.

6. Findings

From our analysis we have found that the popularity of The Big Bang Theory is influenced by a number of factors regarding the content and production of its episodes. The biggest change in the ratings of episodes was exhibited as the show progressed over time. The show saw some of its most consistently high ratings in the first seasons, before a gradual but notable drop in popularity into the later stages. There was little evidence for a pattern relating to any of the show’s several writers and directors including renowned writer Chuck Lorre, known as the ‘King of Sitcoms’.

The strength of the connection between season number and ratings made it more difficult to determine whether any other aspects of the show had an impact on how it was received. For example, where an episode falls within a season, the total number of lines in an episode, and the introduction of Amy and Bernadette as major characters all, at a glance, appeared to have detrimental effects on the popularity. However, we went on to find that these criteria were met far more often in the later, less popular seasons, so their apparent influences on the ratings turned out to be unsupported by the data. Conversely, the underlying impact of the season masked some surprising dynamics in the data. Despite the more popular episodes being aired on Mondays, airing on a Thursday improved ratings after taking the season into account. Moreover, although Leonard saw more involvement in earlier seasons, him having more lines was associated with lower ratings.
